1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,780
Kimi's latest K three is buzzing summed up in three words,

2
00:00:02,780 --> 00:00:04,000
big, good, and open source!

3
00:00:04,240 --> 00:00:06,580
But now, each large language model bests the last

4
00:00:06,580 --> 00:00:08,240
and tomorrow, they get even bigger!

5
00:00:08,420 --> 00:00:10,060
So what are they competing over, exactly?

6
00:00:10,060 --> 00:00:11,490
Well, it boils down to three things,

7
00:00:11,490 --> 00:00:12,840
first, the model’s parameter count

8
00:00:12,840 --> 00:00:14,540
that is the most literal meaning of large

9
00:00:14,540 --> 00:00:15,540
in large language model .

10
00:00:15,680 --> 00:00:17,020
Today, open source model shave

11
00:00:17,020 --> 00:00:18,910
started joining the one T parameter race,

12
00:00:18,910 --> 00:00:21,070
including Meituan's LongCat, DeepSeek, and Kimi,

13
00:00:21,070 --> 00:00:23,520
a feat once solely the domain of closed source models.

14
00:00:23,660 --> 00:00:25,690
The second battleground is context length—back then,

15
00:00:25,690 --> 00:00:26,920
we’d often test this by seeing

16
00:00:26,920 --> 00:00:27,560
if a single chat

17
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:29,780
could read through the whole of “The Three Body Problem”.

18
00:00:30,080 --> 00:00:31,520
For cutting edge large language models,

19
00:00:31,520 --> 00:00:33,310
a million token context length has swiftly gone

20
00:00:33,310 --> 00:00:34,960
from a novel gimmick to a standard feature.

21
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:36,610
Because even a regular person

22
00:00:36,610 --> 00:00:38,190
can spawn tons of long agent

23
00:00:38,190 --> 00:00:40,450
tasks—beyond just chatting on a webpage.

24
00:00:40,450 --> 00:00:42,680
The third battleground is modal support.

25
00:00:42,920 --> 00:00:45,240
Supporting more modalities beyond text

26
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:47,440
greatly impacts the user experience.

27
00:00:47,640 --> 00:00:50,560
For instance, we always ask: when will DeepSeek support images?

28
00:00:50,760 --> 00:00:53,060
That speaks to the hunger for multimodal capabilities,

29
00:00:53,060 --> 00:00:54,720
and one reason Gemini blew up back then

30
00:00:54,720 --> 00:00:56,720
was the debut of its native multimodal feature.

31
00:00:56,920 --> 00:00:58,970
See? The current three point five Flash supports

32
00:00:58,970 --> 00:00:59,930
up to five modalities,

33
00:00:59,930 --> 00:01:00,900
while this new K three

34
00:01:00,900 --> 00:01:02,850
brings all three of those key ones together!

35
00:01:02,930 --> 00:01:03,820
two point eight T

36
00:01:03,820 --> 00:01:04,770
params—the largest

37
00:01:04,770 --> 00:01:07,480
open source model yet—plus a million token context

38
00:01:07,480 --> 00:01:09,050
length AND multimodal support!

39
00:01:09,240 --> 00:01:10,930
Plus, what piqued my curiosity is that,

40
00:01:10,930 --> 00:01:12,030
as an open source model,

41
00:01:12,030 --> 00:01:14,580
it ranked just behind GPT five point six and Fable five

42
00:01:14,580 --> 00:01:15,880
in many key benchmark tests!

43
00:01:16,080 --> 00:01:17,600
and some even snagged number one!

44
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:19,860
Of course, this bigness is just on the surface,

45
00:01:19,860 --> 00:01:21,610
what truly matters are the technologies

46
00:01:21,610 --> 00:01:23,180
behind the scenes that support it

47
00:01:23,180 --> 00:01:25,060
and today, I will break it all down for you!

48
00:01:25,220 --> 00:01:27,740
First, let us see what issues a high parameter count brings.

49
00:01:27,960 --> 00:01:29,790
This is the bedrock of large language model s:

50
00:01:29,790 --> 00:01:30,970
the Transformer architecture;

51
00:01:30,970 --> 00:01:32,890
and within it, the part with the most parameters

52
00:01:32,890 --> 00:01:34,450
are these Feed Forward Network layers,

53
00:01:34,450 --> 00:01:36,500
which are just simple, multi layer neural networks.

54
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:38,040
except that the number of neurons

55
00:01:38,040 --> 00:01:39,340
and thus, parameters is huge.

56
00:01:39,540 --> 00:01:40,790
So, the fix is quite simple,

57
00:01:40,790 --> 00:01:43,100
break it down into many smaller neural networks.

58
00:01:43,180 --> 00:01:44,430
Then, for each new token,

59
00:01:44,430 --> 00:01:45,690
a trained routing layer

60
00:01:45,690 --> 00:01:48,500
directs it to one of those smaller neural networks.

61
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:50,990
This way, the total parameter count stays the same,

62
00:01:50,990 --> 00:01:51,850
but for each token,

63
00:01:51,850 --> 00:01:54,440
far fewer parameters are actually used in computation.

64
00:01:54,680 --> 00:01:57,410
That is the classic MO E Mixture of Experts architecture ,

65
00:01:57,410 --> 00:01:59,220
DeepSeek even put their own spin on it ,

66
00:01:59,220 --> 00:02:01,280
adding  shared experts , dubbed DeepSeek MO E .

67
00:02:01,470 --> 00:02:03,660
Kimi this time also uses an M O E architecture,

68
00:02:03,660 --> 00:02:05,560
eight hundred and ninety six experts, only

69
00:02:05,560 --> 00:02:06,870
sixteen activated at a time.

70
00:02:06,910 --> 00:02:08,820
More precisely, its Latent Mo E scheme

71
00:02:08,820 --> 00:02:10,330
optimizes compute efficiency

72
00:02:10,330 --> 00:02:13,020
via dimension reduction in the expert routing layer.

73
00:02:13,280 --> 00:02:14,220
Anyway, just recall this,

74
00:02:14,220 --> 00:02:15,830
anything with latent prepended shares

75
00:02:15,830 --> 00:02:17,760
one goal, to first shrink then expand dimensions.

76
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:20,720
so you can compute in this low d space to boost efficiency.

77
00:02:21,020 --> 00:02:22,940
The latent in M L A works the same way.

78
00:02:23,220 --> 00:02:25,330
Okay! So, M O E eases computational strain

79
00:02:25,330 --> 00:02:27,820
by cutting down on parameters during inference.

80
00:02:28,020 --> 00:02:29,940
But, the total parameter count stays the same,

81
00:02:29,940 --> 00:02:32,380
and during training, all those params still get trained up.

82
00:02:32,620 --> 00:02:33,830
But as models grow larger,

83
00:02:33,830 --> 00:02:35,630
the Transformer layers get very deep,

84
00:02:35,630 --> 00:02:37,600
which in turn makes the training process

85
00:02:37,600 --> 00:02:38,640
prone to instability.

86
00:02:38,640 --> 00:02:40,590
For these basic deep learning principles,

87
00:02:40,590 --> 00:02:42,840
see my prior video, Understand A I in One Hour.

88
00:02:43,140 --> 00:02:45,420
Of course, a classic structure, Residual Connection,

89
00:02:45,420 --> 00:02:46,820
can fix this issue quite well.

90
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:48,940
So, outside each layer’s transformation,

91
00:02:48,940 --> 00:02:50,000
you add an extra link

92
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,880
and just mindlessly tack on the prior value—super simple!

93
00:02:53,060 --> 00:02:54,670
But there’s a snag: it’s too rigid.

94
00:02:54,670 --> 00:02:57,270
For instance, by the time info from A one reaches A four,

95
00:02:57,270 --> 00:02:58,130
not much is left;

96
00:02:58,130 --> 00:03:00,400
so, ByteDance came up with a new scheme called HC.

97
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:02,560
Simply put, they copy A one multiple times,

98
00:03:02,560 --> 00:03:04,820
and what gets passed on is not just added on,

99
00:03:04,820 --> 00:03:07,080
but rather multiplied by a learnable matrix.

100
00:03:07,270 --> 00:03:08,450
This way, the info passed along

101
00:03:08,450 --> 00:03:10,070
stands a better chance of being retained.

102
00:03:10,190 --> 00:03:12,750
But the snag is, if this learning matrix has no constraints,

103
00:03:12,750 --> 00:03:15,230
its repeated products could spiral out of control again.

104
00:03:15,420 --> 00:03:16,430
So, DeepSeek's m H C

105
00:03:16,430 --> 00:03:19,260
adds fluidity constraints to these learning matrices.

106
00:03:19,540 --> 00:03:20,960
Simply put, it keeps these matrices,

107
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:22,340
no matter how they are multiplied,

108
00:03:22,340 --> 00:03:23,520
within a controllable range

109
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:24,660
thus, an enhancement to H C.

110
00:03:24,920 --> 00:03:26,410
But Kimi chose a different path.

111
00:03:26,410 --> 00:03:27,760
In fact, from a broader view,

112
00:03:27,760 --> 00:03:29,760
no matter how these methods get optimized,

113
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:31,480
they all add to the Residual Stream

114
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:33,160
layer by layer, from bottom to top.

115
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:35,530
whereas Kimi, right within the Residual Stream,

116
00:03:35,530 --> 00:03:36,870
uses the attention mechanism

117
00:03:36,870 --> 00:03:39,020
to perform a weighted sum of prior residuals.

118
00:03:39,260 --> 00:03:40,770
to ensure each layer’s residual info

119
00:03:40,770 --> 00:03:41,940
gets a chance to be noticed.

120
00:03:42,120 --> 00:03:44,790
This is Kimi’s Attention Residuals—many big shots

121
00:03:44,790 --> 00:03:45,990
reposted and liked it

122
00:03:45,990 --> 00:03:46,530
back then,

123
00:03:46,530 --> 00:03:48,000
sparking community chatter,

124
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:49,640
and I even made a video on it!

125
00:03:49,870 --> 00:03:51,630
And this time, the Kimi K three model

126
00:03:51,630 --> 00:03:53,870
puts that tech from that classic paper to use.

127
00:03:53,990 --> 00:03:57,110
Nice! Another open source model with new tech to check out!

128
00:03:57,510 --> 00:03:59,900
Okay! So, the issues stemming from vast parameters

129
00:03:59,900 --> 00:04:01,960
computational load and training stability

130
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:03,670
are solved via the familiar M O E

131
00:04:03,670 --> 00:04:05,480
and Kimi is own Attention Residuals.

132
00:04:05,680 --> 00:04:07,140
So, what about the computation issues

133
00:04:07,140 --> 00:04:08,800
stemming from that million token context?

134
00:04:09,020 --> 00:04:11,030
Back to this Transformer architecture diagram—indeed,

135
00:04:11,030 --> 00:04:12,810
the biggest issue with million token contexts

136
00:04:12,810 --> 00:04:15,140
is that it balloons the computation for the Attention Layer.

137
00:04:15,320 --> 00:04:16,960
since each token in the Attention Layer

138
00:04:16,960 --> 00:04:18,390
must run an attention calculation

139
00:04:18,390 --> 00:04:20,320
with every other token to yield a coefficient.

140
00:04:20,540 --> 00:04:22,140
So, how do we cut down on this compute?

141
00:04:22,300 --> 00:04:25,430
Simple! One way is to shrink the vector length,

142
00:04:25,430 --> 00:04:28,080
for example, M Q A, G Q A, M L A, and so on.

143
00:04:28,120 --> 00:04:28,900
But these still

144
00:04:28,900 --> 00:04:29,750
fall under dense

145
00:04:29,750 --> 00:04:32,340
attention—meaning, the number of vectors computed

146
00:04:32,340 --> 00:04:33,180
stays the same;

147
00:04:33,180 --> 00:04:34,900
only the vector length is reduced.

148
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:36,590
Then, of course, there’s another class

149
00:04:36,590 --> 00:04:38,250
that cuts down on the number of vectors

150
00:04:38,250 --> 00:04:40,780
computed—say, by fixing a computation window to select tokens.

151
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,470
or, via some method, sieve out a few Tokens,

152
00:04:43,470 --> 00:04:44,440
not all of them.

153
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:48,320
Classic methods say, D S A, S W A C S, H C A, and so on

154
00:04:48,320 --> 00:04:50,270
are termed sparse attention,

155
00:04:50,270 --> 00:04:53,130
where the number of vectors grows sparse.

156
00:04:53,380 --> 00:04:54,900
Then, there is the most potent class

157
00:04:54,900 --> 00:04:56,560
that slashes computational complexity

158
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:58,080
straight from n squared down to n

159
00:04:58,080 --> 00:04:59,820
this approach is called Linear Attention,

160
00:04:59,820 --> 00:05:01,300
which includes these methods here.

161
00:05:01,520 --> 00:05:04,220
So, K D A here stands for Kimi Delta Attention

162
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:06,950
an in house Linear Attention scheme from Kimi

163
00:05:06,950 --> 00:05:09,680
that is also been used in this K three model.

164
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,250
Of course, this Linear Attention, in some ways,

165
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:14,040
reverts back to an RNN like method.

166
00:05:14,290 --> 00:05:15,960
So, typically, every few layers,

167
00:05:15,960 --> 00:05:17,470
a Linear Attention is used

168
00:05:17,470 --> 00:05:20,100
and blended with the normal Attention Layer,

169
00:05:20,100 --> 00:05:22,570
hence, it is called Hybrid Attention overall.

170
00:05:23,360 --> 00:05:23,770
To sum up,

171
00:05:23,770 --> 00:05:26,120
a large language model boils down to two key things,

172
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:28,270
the parameter count of its Feed Forward Network,

173
00:05:28,270 --> 00:05:30,280
and the compute load of its Attention Layer.

174
00:05:30,440 --> 00:05:32,950
And this time, K three uses the Latent MoE scheme

175
00:05:32,950 --> 00:05:35,800
to sparsify the Feed Forward Network’s parameter count

176
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:37,280
and compress its length, too.

177
00:05:37,540 --> 00:05:39,410
with K D A Linear Attention, greatly

178
00:05:39,410 --> 00:05:41,660
cutting the Attention Layer's computation.

179
00:05:41,980 --> 00:05:44,810
It also provides a strong case for the effectiveness

180
00:05:44,810 --> 00:05:47,200
of the much debated Hybrid Attention Scheme.

181
00:05:47,440 --> 00:05:50,120
then, they used their novel Attention Residuals

182
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:51,810
to ensure training stability.

183
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:54,090
I wager that many future open source efforts

184
00:05:54,090 --> 00:05:56,530
will widely discuss and adopt these techniques.

185
